# Video: Define a Session for Your App

## Learning Objectives
By the end of this video, you’ll be able to:
- Override Honeycomb’s default `session.id` generator  
- Persist `session.id`s using browser storage  
- Align session attribution with your app’s user session definition  
- Confirm shared session context across user interactions in Honeycomb  

---

### [Visual] Jess looking consfused, trace list with fragmented `session.id` for the same user within what she wants as a defined session, and Meminator being reloadedd in browser. Note on screen: This application has been instrumented with backend and frontend automatic instrumentation!
**[Audio]**  
Jess, a frontend engineer working on a web application called Meminator, has been using Honeycomb to trace user interactions. But when she searches for `session.id` in her traces, she notices something problematic: every time a user reloads the page, Honeycomb shows a completely new session, making it challenging to track a user's complete interaction with her app. 

To fix this, Jess first needs to implement a proper session definition. For Meminator, she defines a session as follows: when a user first visits the app, they get a unique `session.id` that persists until either they close the browser tab or they go idle for more than 5 minutes without generating a meme. Once the session ends, the `session.id` is cleared, and the next time they visit, they'll get a fresh `session.id`.

### [Visual] Show Meminator on browser being refreshed w/ diagram/visual showing how session IDs are assigned by default with each page load, followed by "override" visual cue to indicate defining option
**[Audio]**  
By default, the `HoneycombWebSDK` generates a new `session.id` every time the page loads. This means if a user clicks "GO" five times, reloads the page, and clicks "GO" again, the sixth interaction will appear as completely separate, unrelated trace in Honeycomb—even though they're all part of the same user's session.

To get meaningful insights into user behavior, Jess needs to override this default session logic so her traces actually reflect how people use Meminator.

In this video, you'll learn how to define `session.id` with the `HoneycombWebSDK` to track user journeys the way that makes sense for your application. 

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

